summary: Jodie Whittaker’s Doctor is by far one of my favourites!
body:
Jodie Whittaker’s Doctor is by far one of my favourites!

She’s kind, energetic, empathetic, technical, warm, and a heart full of adventure.

And I think I know why she’s like this…

Remember the very last time we saw Capaldi’s Doctor? He was broken, sad, alone. He’d tried to fix things only to make things worse and lost friends in the process.

Certainly that is the opposite to Whittaker’s Doctor.

So I think the Doctor by this point had had enough. He needed to remind himself just who he was supposed to be. Whittaker’s Doctor feels like a combination of Eccelson, Tennant, and Matt to many fans. And thanks to Chris Chibnall’s writing and the references so far to the classic Doctor Who, Whittaker’s Doctor is starting to behave (for a lack of better word) “fun” again.

Now I understand that the former boys were fun as well, they all had their goofy moments, but let’s remind ourselves their struggles…

9th Doctor was struggling with his guilt and remorse from the Time War, still with a feeling of an aggressive warrior at heart.

10th Doctor started to become much more carefree thanks to his relationship with Rose - however he fell back into remorse after losing her and didn’t fully understand happiness again until his friendship with Donna. However then SHE was forced leave under no fault of her own but more so under pretty much the Doctor’s own fault.

It’s here he started to feel even more broken. He’d lost his friends, or they’d all found someone else. He became a shadow of his carefree self and instead started leaning back into his Time War warrior heart “Timelord Victorious”

It was End of Time and his decision to save will and force him to die did the Doctor think back to what he had done. He didn’t want to go. He didn’t want to leave with the thought of the mistakes he made.

11th Doctor was a lot more bouncy, but he also showed a dark side, and even more so a lonely heart. He straight up confessed to Amy in “The God Complex” that he took her away because he was on his own. The Doctor needs someone to be there to help him not become that Time War warrior from the past he’s tried so hard to not look back on.

Flash forward to 12th’s regeneration and suddenly 13th′s Doctor is starting to make more sense. After 4 regenerations of carrying nothing but pain, guilt, and sadness, The Doctor realised that he needed to remind himself to what he was like before the Time War. He regenerated into a young, carefree spirit. A traveller. 13 clearly remembers her past selves but that’s all she refers to them as in “The Ghost Monument” - her past lives.

And I think the Tardis understood that, because when she and The Doctor finally reunited, her console had changed to mimic something organic, otherworldly and life - very different from the modern, cold, and steely look from the past 4 Doctors.

The Doctor isn’t running away from her past - but rather looking to make a fresh start for the both of them.
